[{"id":"VR877958","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR877956.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The electric potential energy of the two-sphere system shown in the figure is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub electrostatic\"><math alttext=\"U sub electrostatic\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>ELEC</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, and the work done by external forces to move the two spheres from infinitely far away to the locations shown in the figure is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W sub external\"><math alttext=\"W sub external\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>W</mi><mtext>EXT</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. Which of the following correctly identifies the signs of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub electrostatic\"><math alttext=\"U sub electrostatic\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>ELEC</mtext></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W sub external\"><math alttext=\"W sub external\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>W</mi><mtext>EXT</mtext></msub></math></span></span>?</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1\"/><tbody class=\"tbody valign:middle\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\"></td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub electrostatic\"><math alttext=\"U sub electrostatic\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mtext>ELEC</mtext></msub></math></span></span></td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W sub external\"><math alttext=\"W sub external\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>W</mi><mtext>EXT</mtext></msub></math></span></span></td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Negative</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Negative</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">B</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Negative</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Positive</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">C</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Positive</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Negative</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">D</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Positive</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Positive</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR877958_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Two small spheres, one with negative charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"negative Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mo lspace=\"0.05em\" rspace=\"0.05em\">-</mo> <mi>Q</mi> </math></span></span> and one with positive charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"positive Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span>, are fixed in place at the corners of an equilateral triangle and Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is at the third corner. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is midway between the spheres as shown.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows dashed lines connecting two charged spheres, labeled positive Q and negative Q, and two points, labeled Point 1 and Point 2. The two charged spheres and Point 1 are arranged as vertices of an equilateral triangle. The two charged spheres form a vertical segment with negative Q above positive Q, and point 2 is midway between the spheres. A horizontal segment connects point 1 to point 2.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR877956.g02.svg\" /></div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">A</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">B</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">C</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">D</p>"],"answer":0}]